[1] Thailand ex China, 2nd case - Thai MOPH
Date: Fri 17 Jan 2020
Source: Thai Ministry of Public Health [in Thai, machine trans., edited]
https://pr.moph.go.th/?url=pr/detail/2/04/137232/


Thailand, Novel Coronavirus - 2nd case, 17 Jan 2020
---------------------------------------------------
Ministry of Public Health screening for travelers from Wuhan City, People's Republic of China found confirmed coronavirus pneumonia of the 2019 strain from a 2nd individual, which is currently under medical supervision at Bamrasnaradura Institute waiting for the results of repeated lab tests. There has been no outbreak of the new strain of the coronavirus in Thailand.

Today ([17 Jan 2020]) at the Department of Disease Control of the Ministry of Public Health in Nonthaburi Province, Dr. Sukhum Kanchanapimai, Permanent Secretary of the Ministry of Public Health, together with Dr. Suwanchai Wattana Yingcharoenchai, Director-General of the Department of Disease Control, are announcing the situation of people with pneumonia from Wuhan, China, said the Ministry of Public Health. The Department of Disease Control has screened travelers at the airport on [13 Jan 2020], with one additional confirmed case of coronavirus pneumonia from 2019 in a Chinese female aged 74 years. She is currently at the Bamrasnaradura Institute under medical supervision and is showing clinical improvement. If laboratory tests do not detect virus, she will be discharged from the hospital. This is the 2nd case of laboratory-confirmed [novel CoV2019 infection] in Thailand; the 2 parties are not related.

Dr. Sukhum continued that the Ministry of Public Health have carried out surveillance and disease control according to the standard system used for emerging communicable diseases. By screening passengers flying directly from Wuhan, China, at 4 airports, including Suvarnabhumi, Don Mueang, Chiang Mai and Phuket, from 3-16 Jan 2020, a total of 86 flights, 13 624 passengers and crew were screened. Most of the 21 patients who were eligible for the investigation were infected with the influenza virus. A total of 12 patients were treated and returned home. Two patients suffering from pneumonia from the novel coronavirus are still in a treatment room with negative pressure in the Bamrasnaradura Institute.

With the 1st confirmed patient, symptoms have improved a lot, and he no longer has a fever. We are waiting for double confirmation that no virus can be transmitted. The doctor will then allow the patient to go home. As well as the 2nd patient who is currently undergoing treatment and follow up until symptoms disappear. At reinspection, if no virus is found, then the case will be able to return home. The 1st group of patients tested included 16 patients and the 2nd group included 20 persons. No close contacts were found with the new strains of the coronavirus. People do not have to panic in Thailand; there is no outbreak at all.

The Ministry of Public Health also confirmed the public readiness. Both surveillance and epidemic prevention measures in 4 areas are as follows:
1. Ability to monitor disease screening and screening of patients, by screening plane passengers on direct flights from Wuhan City, People's Republic of China
2. Diagnosis and care of patients who are within the investigation criteria
3. Refer patients that meet the criteria to be observed in the negative-pressure room in both public and private hospitals
4. Surveillance in tourist communities around the country

Currently, the World Health Organization has not yet announced a ban on travel to countries where pneumonia is reported. We are asking people to follow the situation closely. If you need to travel to a risky area, be careful. Avoid contact with animals, especially in markets for trading of animals or animal products, or in a crowded place. If coming back from a risky area and one begins to experience symptoms such as fever, cough, sore throat, runny nose, seek immediate medical attention of health personnel. Due to the possibility of pneumonia complications, however, people are an important part in cooperation with the government. If found suspected, we recommend hospital treatment or consult with the Department of Disease Control hotline 1422.

--
Communicated by:
Dan Schar
<dschar@usaid.gov>

[Our submitter Dan Schar commented: "This 2nd case that is epidemiologically unconnected with the 1st traveler-imported case raises important questions around unrecognized human-to-human transmission." I am in full agreement with Dan Schar here. Sticking my neck out to the chopping block, I suspect there may already be significant ongoing transmission of this novel CoV, but fortunately the overwhelming majority of cases are presenting with relatively mild and self-limited symptoms of fever, sore throat and cough, a common presentation during the high season for febrile respiratory illnesses. Many people do not seek medical attention or when seen are given the diagnosis of viral syndrome. I obviously hope I am correct here. - Mod.MPP]

